narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I gained knowledge about American romantic poetry and strengthened my skills in literary analysis.
I learned how to think critically about the poetic question of how we are connected as humans, as well as honed my essay writing and poetry analysis skills.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The strengths of this class were the syllabus and the professor. Professor Barasch was very engaged with the class and I enjoyed the readings. I wish we had received more feedback on our weekly discussion posts and that we didn't have to write them every week (like the weeks where we also had papers).

Strengths: Seminar discussions were always excellent! I learned so much for Professor Barasch and my peers. The readings were always manageable and insightful. 

Weaknesses: I would have appreciated more in-class or assigned/guided background context about American Romanticism and the poets we read.
This course was ok. A little stressful.

I thoroughly enjoyed the course and felt it was soundly structured. The only small thing I wished changed was that the reading responses felt like they should have been due after each class. In many ways I felt like I wanted to reflect on what we spoke about during class and oftentimes the responses were done after doing the reading without any prior discourse. Just feel like it if they were done the other way around it could have been more helpful for me personally.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, I would recommend this course if you are interested in poetry and if you like English.
Yes!! This is a great way to think critically about the human experience, as well as gain a good understanding of the American Romantic tradition.
It wasnt as good as I thought it would be
